## Section 1 — AROW: Ephemeris Data vs. Real Spacecraft Telemetry

**Short answer: AROW uses ACTUAL LIVE TELEMETRY from the spacecraft — not just the ephemeris.**

NASA’s official description (from `nasa.gov`, March 6, 2026):

> *“Using AROW, anyone with internet access can track where Orion and the crew are… AROW visualizes **data collected by sensors on Orion** and sent to the Mission Control Center at NASA’s Johnson Space Center in Houston during its flight. It will provide **constant information using this real-time data** beginning about one minute after liftoff through Orion’s atmospheric reentry.”*

The ephemeris OEM file is a separate, publicly downloadable **planning/prediction product** published by the Flight Dynamics Office — useful for developers and the public, but a distinct artifact from the live telemetry stream driving AROW. NASA will also publish updated ephemeris files during the mission (the filename suffix `v3` confirms versioning is already happening).

### What AROW displays (from NASA screenshots and article)

