## Section 5 — Ephemeris Features NOT in Previous Build Plan (New Additions)

All of the following are derivable from the OEM file and were not in the original build plan:

### 5a — Ground Track (Lat / Lon)

The ECI coordinates can be rotated to Earth-fixed (ECEF) coordinates using Greenwich Sidereal Time, then converted to geodetic latitude and longitude. This enables:

- **A ground track map** showing the spacecraft’s position projected down onto Earth’s surface
- **Sub-satellite point** (the point on Earth directly below Orion)
- **Splashdown target location** — the final vector ends at **lat 17.81°N, lon −146.95°** (Pacific Ocean, northwest of Hawaii), a real and precise splashdown prediction from the Flight Dynamics Office

```javascript
function eciToLatLon(x, y, z, utcDate) {
  const j2000 = new Date('2000-01-01T12:00:00Z');
  const days = (utcDate - j2000) / 86400000;
  const gst = ((280.46061837 + 360.98564736629 * days) % 360) * Math.PI / 180;
  const xe = x * Math.cos(gst) + y * Math.sin(gst);
  const ye = -x * Math.sin(gst) + y * Math.cos(gst);
  const ze = z;
  return {
    lat: Math.atan2(ze, Math.sqrt(xe*xe + ye*ye)) * 180/Math.PI,
    lon: Math.atan2(ye, xe) * 180/Math.PI
  };
}
```

### 5b — Radial vs. Tangential Velocity

Splitting the velocity vector into its radial component (toward/away from Earth) and tangential component (orbital “sideways”) is meaningful and displayable:

- **Radial velocity > 0** = moving away from Earth (climbing)
- **Radial velocity < 0** = falling toward Earth (reentry approach, or coast phase)
- **Tangential velocity** = the orbital component; high during orbit, falls during coast

```javascript
function radialTangential(x, y, z, vx, vy, vz) {
  const r = Math.sqrt(x*x + y*y + z*z);
  const radial = (x*vx + y*vy + z*vz) / r;
  const speed = Math.sqrt(vx*vx + vy*vy + vz*vz);
  const tangential = Math.sqrt(Math.max(0, speed*speed - radial*radial));
  return { radial, tangential };
}
```

### 5c — Burn / Maneuver Detection

The ephemeris cadence tightens near maneuvers (60s vs. ~292s nominal). Delta-V spikes are detectable:

```javascript
const accel = Math.abs(speed[i+1] - speed[i]) / interval_s;
if (accel > threshold) flagAsBurn(vectors[i].t);
```

Known detectable events from this file: TLI (translunar injection), trajectory correction maneuvers, any other burns in the April 2–10 window.

### 5d — Data Freshness Indicator

The OEM header contains `CREATION_DATE = 2026-04-02T14:06:23`. Display this to users as “Ephemeris data as of [date]” and the `USEABLE_STOP_TIME` as “Coverage through [date].” Both are parseable from the file header.

### 5e — Ephemeris Version Tracking

The filename already shows `v3`, meaning this is the third planning update. When a newer file is posted by NASA, it will have a newer `CREATION_DATE`. Build logic to detect version changes and prompt a re-fetch.

### 5f — Authoritative Mission End Time

`USEABLE_STOP_TIME = 2026-04-10T23:53:12.332` — use this as the denominator for mission progress %, replacing the hardcoded 234-hour estimate.

### 5g — Predicted Splashdown Location Display

Last ephemeris vector: **lat 17.81°N, lon −146.95°** at 143 km altitude. This is the Flight Dynamics Office’s predicted atmospheric entry interface point — not splashdown itself (which happens after reentry heating below the ephemeris coverage), but it pins the corridor precisely. Show on map with a marker.

### 5h — Reentry Corridor Visualization

The final ~90 minutes of the ephemeris have 1-minute cadence and track the spacecraft from 7,700 km altitude down to 143 km. This reentry approach can be animated or highlighted separately as a dramatic mission segment.

### 5i — Real Maximum Distance Record

The ephemeris confirms **406,775 km** from Earth’s surface at `2026-04-06T23:07:39 UTC`. Display this as the confirmed record value (not an editorial estimate), sourced from NASA/JSC/FOD.

### 5j — Velocity in km/s

Currently neither the existing site nor the previous build plan showed velocity in km/s — only km/h. For deep-space context, km/s is the standard unit used by NASA and is more intuitive at these scales (e.g., “0.6 km/s” vs “2,143 km/h”). Add both.

